{"title_page": "Betty Rea", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n'''Elizabeth Marion Rea''' (n\u00e9e Bevan, 1904\u20131965) was an English sculptor and [[educationalist]].{{Infobox artist\n| name = Betty Rea\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 6 August 1904\n| birth_place = London\n| death_date = 2 April 1965\n| death_place = \n| nationality = British\n| field = Sculpture\n| training = [[Downe House School]]<br>[[Regent Street Polytechnic]]<br />[[Royal College of Art]]\n| spouse = James Rea (1926\u20131942)\n| awards = \n| website = \n}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBetty Rea was born in London in 1904. Her father was Dr. Arthur Bevan and her mother's maiden name was Barnardo; Dr.[[Thomas John Barnardo]] was her great-uncle.\n\nShe was educated at [[Downe House School]] (in Kent at that time) and began to study painting at the [[University of Westminster|Regent Street Polytechnic]] in 1922, almost at once changing to sculpture and transferring her studies to the [[Royal College of Art]] in 1924. Her teacher there was [[Ernest A. Cole]]. [[Henry Moore]] was a student teacher at the RCA at that time, and became a friend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sohamgrammar.org.uk/threeboys_sculpt.htm|title=Soham Grammarians : The Three Boys bronze, Betty Rea|website=sohamgrammar.org.uk|access-date=22 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1926 she married law student James Russell Rea (1902\u20131954), whose father became [[Baron Rea]], a Liberal peer. Together they had two sons, [[Nicolas Rea, 3rd Baron Rea|Nicholas]] and Julian, who were born in 1928 and 1931. The couple divorced in 1942.\n\n== Life and work ==\nDuring the 1930s, partly influenced by her friendship with Professor [[John Desmond Bernal]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-66318;jsessionid=82BA123CD82A0E9D3F00B88921AF56A2|title=Rea [n\u00e9e Bevan], Betty Marion (1904\u20131965), sculptor {{!}} Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|website=www.oxforddnb.com|access-date=22 October 2019}}</ref> Betty Rea was greatly involved in [[anti-fascist]], [[leftwing]] politics. She was a founding member of [[Artists' International Association]] (AIA),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.henry-moore.org/archives-and-library/archive-of-sculptors-papers/archive-collections/betty-rea|title=Betty Rea Archive Collection at the Henry Moore Institute, Leeds|last=Mayoh|first=Claire|date=10 September 2015|website=henry-moore.org|url-status=live|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref> and served as secretary from 1934 to 1936.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://paulmelloncentre.cirqahosting.com/HeritageScripts/Hapi.dll/relatedsearch?SearchTerm=~[!D16013]~&PlainTerm=D16013&Dispfmt=F|title=Betty Rea 1905\u20131965 sculpture|last=Robertson|first=Bryan|last2=Herbert|first2=Basil|last3=Black|first3=Misha|last4=Rose|first4=Jasper|publisher=Zwemmer Gallery|year=1965|isbn=|location=Paul Mellon Centre|pages=16, 29}}</ref> Founded in 1933, the AIA sought to oppose [[imperialism]], [[fascism]] and [[colonialism]] through art.\n\nRea was also an active member of the Communist Party Artists group, the Artists\u2019 Refugee Committee, as well as Chair of the Arts Peace Campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://homerton250.org/people/betty-rea/|title=Peter Cunningham, exploring the archive, discovers Betty Rea, who taught at Homerton College between 1949 and 1964.|last=Cunningham|first=Peter|website=homerton250.org|url-status=live|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nCommunal care for children and their education was one of Rea's socialist interests. In 1934, following a trip to the Soviet Union, she published an article, 'Children and Art in Soviet Russia', which praised the educational advances being made in Russia.<ref>{{Cite book|title=immediations Vol.3 No.1|last=Goodeve|first=Meghan|publisher=Courtauld Institute of Art|year=2012|isbn=|editor-last=Faulkner|editor-first=Catherine|location=|page=|pages=47\u201363|issn=1742-7444}}</ref>\n\nIn 1937 she worked upon a mural in the Unofficial Peace Pavilion at the Paris World Fair.\n\nAt the outset of the Second World War, Rea's personal life eclipsed her role as an exhibiting artist. For most of the war, Rea taught painting and model-making in evacuated children's homes in [[Huntingdon]] and other villages in the surrounding Cambridgeshire countryside. She set up home with her colleague, [[Nan Youngman]], first in a [[Travel trailer|caravan]] in the grounds of [[Hinchingbrooke House]], then in [[Godmanchester]], and in 1946 at 'Papermills' in [[Cambridge]]. The children's paintings from this time were included in several [[British Council]] exhibitions sent abroad and some are illustrated in [[Herbert Read]]'s \"Education Through Art\".\n\nIt was not until 1942 that Rea would return to creating sculpture, when the members of the AIA, encouraged by the British government, staged the exhibition ''For Liberty'' to increase wartime propaganda and raise the public's spirits. Rea's sculpture ''New World'' was displayed in a section of the exhibition under the thematic title of 'this is how we are fighting'; the other two sections of the exhibition investigated the themes 'this is what will happen if we lose the war' and 'this is what we are fighting for'.\n\nFrom 1949 Rea taught sculpture at [[Homerton College]], continuing this part-time until 1964, she also worked for some years as craft examiner for the [[Cambridge]] Local Examinations Syndicate.\n\nBetty Rea died in April 1965. At the time of her death she was working on a clay sculpture commissioned for Hockerill College, to be cast in bronze.\n\n== Works ==\nBetty Rea's 1959 ''Stretching Figure'' (bronze resin), was described by Gillian Whiteley as \"expressing the diverse emotions, activities, and grace of youth\". It is held by the [[Herbert Art Gallery and Museum]], [[Coventry]].<ref>Gillian Whiteley, \u2018Rea , Betty Marion (1904\u20131965)\u2019, [[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]], Oxford University Press, 2004; online edn, May 2006</ref>\n\nHer last work, ''Swimmers'', completed posthumously by [[John W Mills]], stands in the grounds of [[Cambridge]] Parkside swimming pool.\n\nRea's work is held in many collections, including [[Leeds Museums & Galleries|Leeds Museums and Galleries]]; various education authority collections; Cambridge Institute of Education; University of Warwick; Hockerill College, Bishop's Stortford; Harlow Art Trust; Herbert Museum and Art Gallery, Coventry.\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n\n=== Solo exhibitions ===\n\n*''Betty Rea'', 14 June \u2013 9 July, Zwemmer Gallery, London.\n*''Betty Rea 1904\u20131965'',  \u2013 3 June July 1965, Zwemmer Gallery, London.\n* ''Memorial Exhibition'', 1966, Cambridge Society of Painters and Sculptors, Arts Council Gallery, Cambridge.\n* ''Betty Rea 1904\u20131965'', May 1985, Royston Museum.\n\n=== Group exhibitions ===\n\n* ''Artists for Peace'', Woburn Place, London 1952.\n* Co-organised ''Looking at People'', [[Whitworth Art Gallery]], Manchester 1955 and expanded version at [[South London Gallery]], which then travelled to Moscow in 1957.\n* ''Artists of Fame and Promise'', Leicester Galleries, London 1956, 57. \n* Women's International Art Club exhibition 1957. \n* ''Three Humanist Sculptors'', Zwemmer Gallery, London 1960.\n\nBetty Rea exhibited annually with Cambridge Society of Painters and Sculptors from 1955.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sculpture.gla.ac.uk/view/person.php?id=msib5_1241025160|title=Betty Marion Rea \u2013 Mapping the Practice and Profession of Sculpture in Britain and Ireland 1851\u20131951|publisher=University of Glasgow|access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref> Posthumously, her work was included in the AIA exhibition, curated by Lynda Morris, held at the Museum of Modern Art in Oxford in 1983.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://warwick.ac.uk/services/art/artist/bettyrea|title=University of Warwick Art Collection \u2013 Artists \u2013 Betty Rea|publisher=University of Warwick|access-date=22 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nMore recently, Betty Rea's sculpture was the subject of research at the [[Henry Moore Institute]], Leeds in 2003, resulting in the exhibition ''A Fine Tomorrow: Sculpture and Socialism in mid-century Britain'' (29 May \u2013 29 August 2003), with a companion publication of the same name by Matthew Withey.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/65637909|title=A fine tomorrow : sculpture and socialism in mid-century Britain|last=Withey, Matthew.|first=|date=2003|publisher=Henry Moore Institute|others=Leeds (England). City Art Gallery.|year=|isbn=1900081938|location=Leeds|pages=|oclc=65637909}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081201180809/http://www.cambridge.gov.uk/public/public-art-audit/18.html Betty Rea/[[John W Mills]] 'Bathers' sculpture]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071027023502/http://www.visitharlow.com/what-to-see-and-do/theatres-and-galleries/collections/sculpture-collection/artist_70 'Kore' [[Harlow]]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rea, Betty}}\n[[Category:People educated at Downe House School]]\n[[Category:English sculptors]]\n[[Category:1904 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Homerton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:20th-century British sculptors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n'''Elizabeth Marion Rea''' (n\u00e9e Bevan, 1904\u20131965) was an English sculptor and [[educationalist]].{{Infobox artist\n| name = Betty Rea\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 6 August 1904\n| birth_place = London\n| death_date = 2 April 1965\n| death_place = \n| nationality = British\n| field = Sculpture\n| training = [[Downe House School]]<br>[[Regent Street Polytechnic]]<br />[[Royal College of Art]]\n| spouse = James Rea (1926\u20131942)\n| awards = \n| website = \n}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBetty Rea was born in London in 1904. Her father was Dr. Arthur Bevan and her mother's maiden name was Barnardo; Dr.[[Thomas John Barnardo]] was her great-uncle.\n\nShe was educated at [[Downe House School]] (in Kent at that time) and began to study painting at the [[University of Westminster|Regent Street Polytechnic]] in 1922, almost at once changing to sculpture and transferring her studies to the [[Royal College of Art]] in 1924. Her teacher there was [[Ernest A. Cole]]. [[Henry Moore]] was a student teacher at the RCA at that time, and became a friend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sohamgrammar.org.uk/threeboys_sculpt.htm|title=Soham Grammarians : The Three Boys bronze, Betty Rea|website=sohamgrammar.org.uk|access-date=22 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1926 she married law student James Russell Rea (1902\u20131954), whose father became [[Baron Rea]], a Liberal peer. Together they had two sons, [[Nicolas Rea, 3rd Baron Rea|Nicholas]] and Julian, who were born in 1928 and 1931. The couple divorced in 1942.\n\n== Life and work ==\nDuring the 1930s, partly influenced by her friendship with Professor [[John Desmond Bernal]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-66318;jsessionid=82BA123CD82A0E9D3F00B88921AF56A2|title=Rea [n\u00e9e Bevan], Betty Marion (1904\u20131965), sculptor {{!}} Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|website=www.oxforddnb.com|access-date=22 October 2019}}</ref> Betty Rea was greatly involved in [[anti-fascist]], [[leftwing]] politics. She was a founding member of [[Artists' International Association]] (AIA),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.henry-moore.org/archives-and-library/archive-of-sculptors-papers/archive-collections/betty-rea|title=Betty Rea Archive Collection at the Henry Moore Institute, Leeds|last=Mayoh|first=Claire|date=10 September 2015|website=henry-moore.org|url-status=live|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref> and served as secretary from 1934 to 1936.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://paulmelloncentre.cirqahosting.com/HeritageScripts/Hapi.dll/relatedsearch?SearchTerm=~[!D16013]~&PlainTerm=D16013&Dispfmt=F|title=Betty Rea 1905\u20131965 sculpture|last=Robertson|first=Bryan|last2=Herbert|first2=Basil|last3=Black|first3=Misha|last4=Rose|first4=Jasper|publisher=Zwemmer Gallery|year=1965|isbn=|location=Paul Mellon Centre|pages=16, 29}}</ref> Founded in 1933, the AIA sought to oppose [[imperialism]], [[fascism]] and [[colonialism]] through art.\n\nRea was also an active member of the Communist Party Artists group, the Artists\u2019 Refugee Committee, as well as Chair of the Arts Peace Campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://homerton250.org/people/betty-rea/|title=Peter Cunningham, exploring the archive, discovers Betty Rea, who taught at Homerton College between 1949 and 1964.|last=Cunningham|first=Peter|website=homerton250.org|url-status=live|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nCommunal care for children and their education was one of Rea's socialist interests. In 1934, following a trip to the Soviet Union, she published an article, 'Children and Art in Soviet Russia', which praised the educational advances being made in Russia.<ref>{{Cite book|title=immediations Vol.3 No.1|last=Goodeve|first=Meghan|publisher=Courtauld Institute of Art|year=2012|isbn=|editor-last=Faulkner|editor-first=Catherine|location=|page=|pages=47\u201363|issn=1742-7444}}</ref>\n\nIn 1937 she worked upon a mural in the Unofficial Peace Pavilion at the Paris World Fair.\n\nAt the outset of the Second World War, Rea's personal life eclipsed her role as an exhibiting artist. For most of the war, Rea taught painting and model-making in evacuated children's homes in [[Huntingdon]] and other villiages in the surrounding Cambridgeshire countryside. She set up home with her colleague, [[Nan Youngman]], first in a [[Travel trailer|caravan]] in the grounds of [[Hinchingbrooke House]], then in [[Godmanchester]], and in 1946 at 'Papermills' in [[Cambridge]]. The children's paintings from this time were included in several [[British Council]] exhibitions sent abroad and some are illustrated in [[Herbert Read]]'s \"Education Through Art\".\n\nIt was not until 1942 that Rea would return to creating sculpture, when the members of the AIA, encouraged by the British government, staged the exhibition ''For Liberty'' to increase wartime propaganda and raise the public's spirits. Rea's sculpture ''New World'' was displayed in a section of the exhibition under the thematic title of 'this is how we are fighting'; the other two sections of the exhibition investigated the themes 'this is what will happen if we lose the war' and 'this is what we are fighting for'.\n\nFrom 1949 Rea taught sculpture at [[Homerton College]], continuing this part-time until 1964, she also worked for some years as craft examiner for the [[Cambridge]] Local Examinations Syndicate.\n\nBetty Rea died in April 1965. At the time of her death she was working on a clay sculpture commissioned for Hockerill College, to be cast in bronze.\n\n== Works ==\nBetty Rea's 1959 ''Stretching Figure'' (bronze resin), was described by Gillian Whiteley as \"expressing the diverse emotions, activities, and grace of youth\". It is held by the [[Herbert Art Gallery and Museum]], [[Coventry]].<ref>Gillian Whiteley, \u2018Rea , Betty Marion (1904\u20131965)\u2019, [[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]], Oxford University Press, 2004; online edn, May 2006</ref>\n\nHer last work, ''Swimmers'', completed posthumously by [[John W Mills]], stands in the grounds of [[Cambridge]] Parkside swimming pool.\n\nRea's work is held in many collections, including [[Leeds Museums & Galleries|Leeds Museums and Galleries]]; various education authority collections; Cambridge Institute of Education; University of Warwick; Hockerill College, Bishop's Stortford; Harlow Art Trust; Herbert Museum and Art Gallery, Coventry.\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n\n=== Solo exhibitions ===\n\n*''Betty Rea'', 14 June \u2013 9 July, Zwemmer Gallery, London.\n*''Betty Rea 1904\u20131965'',  \u2013 3 June July 1965, Zwemmer Gallery, London.\n* ''Memorial Exhibition'', 1966, Cambridge Society of Painters and Sculptors, Arts Council Gallery, Cambridge.\n* ''Betty Rea 1904\u20131965'', May 1985, Royston Museum.\n\n=== Group exhibitions ===\n\n* ''Artists for Peace'', Woburn Place, London 1952.\n* Co-organised ''Looking at People'', [[Whitworth Art Gallery]], Manchester 1955 and expanded version at [[South London Gallery]], which then travelled to Moscow in 1957.\n* ''Artists of Fame and Promise'', Leicester Galleries, London 1956, 57. \n* Women's International Art Club exhibition 1957. \n* ''Three Humanist Sculptors'', Zwemmer Gallery, London 1960.\n\nBetty Rea exhibited annually with Cambridge Society of Painters and Sculptors from 1955.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sculpture.gla.ac.uk/view/person.php?id=msib5_1241025160|title=Betty Marion Rea \u2013 Mapping the Practice and Profession of Sculpture in Britain and Ireland 1851\u20131951|publisher=University of Glasgow|access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref> Posthumously, her work was included in the AIA exhibition, curated by Lynda Morris, held at the Museum of Modern Art in Oxford in 1983.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://warwick.ac.uk/services/art/artist/bettyrea|title=University of Warwick Art Collection \u2013 Artists \u2013 Betty Rea|publisher=University of Warwick|access-date=22 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nMore recently, Betty Rea's sculpture was the subject of research at the [[Henry Moore Institute]], Leeds in 2003, resulting in the exhibition ''A Fine Tomorrow: Sculpture and Socialism in mid-century Britain'' (29 May \u2013 29 August 2003), with a companion publication of the same name by Matthew Withey.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/65637909|title=A fine tomorrow : sculpture and socialism in mid-century Britain|last=Withey, Matthew.|first=|date=2003|publisher=Henry Moore Institute|others=Leeds (England). City Art Gallery.|year=|isbn=19000